While construction on the new facility has not yet concluded and as such there have been no accidental releases in the previous five years that resulted in off-site death, injury, or environmental response or restoration activities, the worst-case release scenario does pose a risk of off-site public impact.  Based on a series of offsite consequence analyses (OCAs) performed using the EPA's RMP Offsite Consequence Analysis Guidance Manual, May 24, 1996, the worst case consequence scenario resulting from a catastrophic release of ammonia from the largest single vessel (the High Temperature Recirculator) would result in a toxic endpoint of 0.9 miles.  At this distance, several public and environmental receptors located beyond the property boundaries surrounding the facility would be impacted by such a release.  Therefore, the facility is not eligible for the Program 1 level prevention program.



